RABIES (EBLV), HUMAN EXPOSURE - DENMARK
***************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Fri 3 Nov 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Eurosurveillance weekly release 2006, Vol 11, Issue 11 [edited]
<http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ew/2006/061103.asp#4>

Case report
-----------
In June 2006, an 18-month-old girl living in southern Denmark was
admitted to hospital following a bat bite. The girl had been playing
on her own in front of the family farm, when she was found crying,
and with a bat attached by the mouth to one of her hands. The bat was
removed and killed, and the girl's mother cleaned the wound
thoroughly with soap and water. The girl was referred to the nearest
paediatric medical service for management of the potential rabies
exposure. On examination in hospital, a pin prick-like wound was
found on the patient's right hand. Post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP)
was started (human rabies immunoglobulin was administered and a
course of rabies vaccination was begun).
During the summer, the patient's parents had noticed several bats
lying on the ground around the farm, unable to fly, but they had not
previously reported this. Because the dead bat that bit the child had
been crushed, it was not possible to test brain tissue for rabies
virus. Nine dead bats were then collected from the farm and tested at
the Danish Institute for Food and Veterinary Research. Of these 9
bats, 4 tested positive for a bat variant of rabies virus, European
Bat Lyssavirus (EBLV). The species of the bats is not known.
Rabies in bats in Denmark
-------------------------
Since 1996, the Danish Institute for Food and Veterinary Research has
analysed between 2 and 88 bats per year (Table 1), and between 0 and
11 bats per year have been found to be positive for EBLV. During the
same time period, between 4 and 18 people have been treated with PEP
after bat exposure each year in Denmark (Table 1). Where possible,
the bats connected with exposure are tested, but often bats are not
captured after their contact with humans, and therefore in most
cases, the bats tested are from other sources. Of the total number of
bats examined during this period in connection with human exposure,
58 percent were positive for EBLV.
Table. Number of bats tested for rabies in Denmark, 1996-2005:
totals, and in connection with human exposures.
Year / Bats tested* / No. +ve / No.persons given PEP / EBLV +ve
batsve** / EBLV -ve bats**
1996 / 2 / 0 / 4 / 0 / 0
1997 / 31 / 11 / 11 / 1 / 0
1998 /45 / 10 / 18 / 3 / 1
1999 / 88 / 9 / 12 / 1 / 0
2000 / 38 / 2 / 11 / 1 / 1
2001 /20 / 2 / 8 / 0 / 0
2002 / 43 / 2 / 14 / 0 / 1
2003 / 32 / 3 / 10 / 0 / 0
