[These data reveal the extent of rabies virus infection in bats in
Denmark, but are less informative than they might have been since no
attempt has been made to discriminate between the 2 European bat
lyssaviruses (EBLV-1 and EBLV-2). Limited surveillance suggests that
EBLV-1 and ELV-2 have different distributions in Europe [e.g. see
ProMED-mail references below).
Rabies virus, the causative agent of classical rabies, is the type
species of the genus Lyssavirus. Six other species are now
recognized: Mokola virus, Lagos bat virus, Duvenhage virus, European
bat lyssavirus 1, European bat lyssavirus 2 , and Australian bat
lyssavirus. The first 5 rabies-related species are restricted to the
Old World, whereas the 6th, a new lyssavirus isolated from
fruit-eating bats in 1996, is restricted to Australia, an island
country considered to be rabies-free for more than 100 years.
Bats are vectors for 6 of the 7 species and are the exclusive vector
for 5 of the 7 species. Rabies virus is the only one of these viruses
whose primary hosts are terrestrial vectors (mainly carnivores). The
species Rabies virus has spread worldwide in domesticated and wild
animals, whereas the other 6 species have narrower geographic and
host range distributions (and so far are confined to the Old world
and Australia) The 7 species of lyssaviruses are related by N and G
gene phylogeny, and by serology. The Danish surveillance data confirm
that post-exposure treatment with classical rabies virus vaccine and
immunoglobulin protects the recipients of bat bites from neurological
damage and ultimate death from the disease. - Mod.CP]
